Modeling the relationship between Diameter (DBH) and Height (H).

Step 1: Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

The Scatter plot to visually assess the shape of the curve.

# Plot the scatter diagram
ggplot(data_tree, aes(x = DBH, y = H)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6, color = "darkgreen") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Diameter - Height Relationship",
       x = "Diameter at Breast Height (DBH - cm)",
       y = "Total Height (H - m)")

Step 2: Selecting Ecological Models

There are many mathematical functions to describe the H-D relationship. The most common in forestry are: The Chapman-Richards function (also known as the generalized logistic function) is widely cited for modeling height-diameter (H-D) relationships in forestry, with key papers by Richards (1959) (for the original growth function) and numerous applications by researchers like Sharma & Parton (2007), Temesgen & Gadow (2004), Calama & Montero (2004), and more recent studies (e.g., Nazari Sendi et al., 2023, Ismail et al., 2025) demonstrating its versatility, often alongside mixed-effects modeling approaches for better accuracy across different species and forest conditions.

  • Chapman-Richards Function: \(H=1.3 + a.(1-e^{-b.DBH})^c\)

    • 1.3 : Height at breast height.

    • a: Maximum height (Asymptote).

    • b: Growth rate.

    • c: Shape parameter of the curve.

    Find Maximum height

    max(data_tree$H)
    ## [1] 19

Step3: Running the Non-linear Model (nls)

We use the nlsLM function (from the minpack.lm package) instead of the standard nls in R because it uses the Levenberg-Marquardt algorithm, which helps find convergence more easily.

# --- Model 2: Chapman-Richards ---
# Formula: H = 1.3 + a * (1 - exp(-b * DBH))^c
# Note: Choosing reasonable start values is crucial. 
fit_cr <- nlsLM(H ~ 1.3 + a * (1 - exp(-b * DBH))^c, 
                data = data_tree, 
                start = list(a = 20, b = 0.05, c = 1))

# View results summary
summary(fit_cr)
##

Step 4: Visualizing the Regression Curves

# Create smooth prediction data
dbh_seq <- seq(min(data_tree$DBH), max(data_tree$DBH), length.out = 100)

# Predict values from the  models
pred_cr <- predict(fit_cr, newdata = data.frame(DBH = dbh_seq))

# Combine for plotting
plot_data <- data.frame(DBH = dbh_seq, 
                        ChapmanRichards = pred_cr)

# Plot comparison
ggplot() +
  # Original data
  geom_point(data = data_tree, aes(x = DBH, y = H), alpha = 0.5, color = "gray50") +
  # Chapman-Richards line (Blue)
  geom_line(data = plot_data, aes(x = DBH, y = ChapmanRichards, color = "Chapman-Richards"), linewidth = 1) +
  labs(title = "Height - Diameter Model of Pinus krempfii",
       subtitle = "Data: Bidoup Plot",
       x = "DBH (cm)", y = "Height (m)",
       color = "Model") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

Biomass and carbon stock

Biomass

  • Above-ground biomass (AGB)

  • Below-ground biomass (BGB)

AGB calculation

Chave et al (2005). Tree allometry and improved estimation of carbon stocks and balance in tropical forests. Oecologia, 145(1): 8799.

  • AGB=Total aboveground biomass (kg)

  • D=DBH (cm)

  • H=Height (m)

  • \(\)=Wood density (g/cm3)

  • BA=Basal area (cm2)

Habitat Equation in Chave et al (2005)
Tropical forest MOIST with Height \(AGB = exp(-2.977 + ln( * D^2 * H))\)
Tropical forest MOIST only DBH \(AGB = * exp(-1.499 + 2.148 * ln(D) + 0.207 * (ln(D))^2 0.0281 * (ln(D))^3)\)

Get Wood density of Pinus krempfii

library(BIOMASS)  

woodensity <- getWoodDensity(
  genus = "Pinus",
  species = "Pinus krempfii",
  family = "Pinaceae"
)  
woodensity
##     family genus        species    meanWD       sdWD levelWD nInd
## 1 Pinaceae Pinus Pinus krempfii 0.4402721 0.09413391   genus   57

Add Wood density to data

data_tree$meanWD <- woodensity$meanWD

Biomass

data_tree <- data_tree %>% 
  mutate(AGB_onlyD = meanWD * exp(-1.499 + 2.148*log(DBH) + 0.207*log(DBH)^2 - 0.0281*log(DBH)^3),
         AGB_withH = exp(-2.977 + log(meanWD * DBH^2*H))) 
(AGB_onlyD <- sum(data_tree$AGB_onlyD)/1000) #Ton/ha 
## [1] 376.3073
(AGB_withH <- sum(data_tree$AGB_withH)/1000) #Ton/ha 
## [1] 149.2933

BGB calculation

The ratio developed by Mokany et al.(2006). Critical analysis of root:shoot ratios in terrestrial biomes. Global Change Biology, 12: 84-96 offers specific ratios based on forest type and climate zone and are applicable when the aboveground biomass estimate (shoot) is reported at the stand level

(BGB_onlyD = 0.235 * AGB_onlyD)
## [1] 88.43222
(BGB_withH = 0.235 * AGB_withH)
## [1] 35.08393

Total biomass of 1 hecta

(TB_onlyD <- AGB_onlyD + BGB_onlyD)
## [1] 464.7395
(TB_withH <- AGB_withH + BGB_withH)
## [1] 184.3772

Carbon stock

The quantity of carbon can then be estimated by converting biomass to carbon using the IPCC default carbon fraction of 0.47. After that, the carbon stock was multiplied by 44/12 (the carbon atom ratio in the molecular weight of CO2) to get the CO2 equivalent value.

#Carbon stock (ton/ha)
(TC_onlyD <- TB_onlyD * 0.47) 
## [1] 218.4276
(TC_withH <- TB_withH * 0.47) 
## [1] 86.65731
# CO2 (ton)
(CO2_onlyD <- TC_onlyD * 44/22)
## [1] 436.8551
(CO2_withH <- TC_withH * 44/22)
## [1] 173.3146
